## Administration

This is a [redirect](/Wikipedia:Redirect). A placeholder, really. Like a sketch before the real work begins. The following [categories](/Wikipedia:Categorizing_redirects) are used to sort this kind of… *thing*. It’s a bureaucratic classification, I suppose. Even the void has its filing system.

*   [To a disambiguation page](/Category:Redirects_to_disambiguation_pages) : This designation means it’s pointing to a page that’s meant to clarify multiple meanings. A sort of linguistic triage. It’s for when you’re not sure which specific shade of meaning you’re aiming for. This particular redirect is intended for use in links from other articles that need to refer to the disambiguation page itself, rather than get lost in the noise. It’s about pointing to the map, not the territory. If a title is ambiguous but doesn't explicitly end with "(disambiguation)", it gets a different tag: &#123;&#123;[R from ambiguous term](/Template:R_from_ambiguous_term)&#125;&#125;. And if a disambiguation page itself turns out to be… insufficient, like when there are multiple notable individuals with the same descriptor, say "(painter)", then &#123;&#123;[R from incomplete disambiguation](/Template:R_from_incomplete_disambiguation)&#125;&#125; is the appropriate template to mark that particular failure.

The [protection levels](/Wikipedia:Protection_policy) are automatically observed, noted, and categorized. It’s all very… controlled. Like a carefully constructed cage.